Inflation in Europe has slipped into food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid increase in food prices.
In November, the increase in prices, in the 13 countries of the euro area, was greater compared to the forecast, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the statistics office of the European Community located in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts have only reported 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the interest rate by saying that the decline in interests, with the growth of primer prices and the fall in the unemployment rate, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is Catch 22 for the ECB: "it is necessary to deter" inflation in order to no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 percent is a record in the last 12 years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereals futures market ratings have increased by 88 percent and the price of soybeans has also reached its highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent and last month a barrel of black gold cost almost US$100.
According to the ECB, in 2008, the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, the next 3 to 4 months, the average annual rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup indicates a crisis of the government
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly in early December. Thus since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Polling Institute) has never seen such weak socialist support before, namely 13 percent.
For fidele voters, the difference would represent, because of the greater determination of the voters of the opposition, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Forum of Hungarian Democrats) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent in the entire population.
On voters who are so fond of voting, the number of supporters of both parties has increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate from the previous low point, the proportion of those who have judged that the economic situation of the country is particularly serious has never been higher, it is rising to 41 percent and according to 46 percent complementary the situation is quite serious.
After the more optimistic outlook for last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only a tenth predicts an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in previous Gallup polls, said the Prime Minister was doing his job rather badly than good.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcsány while 38 percent support Viktor Orbán.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister and 27 percent trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society thinking that discontent with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change of government.
While after the riots last October, 35 percent of those polled wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, currently this rate is only 20 percent. The relative majority (33 per cent) believe that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
To the question concerning the intention to vote, 60 per cent of the respondents replied that they would certainly go to vote and the additional 20 percent said that they would probably go to vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to organize next Sunday", only 55 percent of respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent complementary would probably participate. According to the current intentions, the result of the referendum would be no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to higher education enrollment fees, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees, and 84 percent would say no to hospital expenses.
When we look only at the same proportions among those who have expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, 81, 84 and 89 per cent of the voters, respectively, would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay expenses.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has increased its prices by twenty percent
The hypermarkets in the Budaörs trade triangle maintained the average price increase of 16 percent last year is the difference that this year the VAT rate has not increased.
Article by Napi Gazdaság (Daily Economy)
This year, in the commercial triangle of Budaörs, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by 16 percent on average, a significantly higher value increase of one thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already soared" in the grocery stores last December, no longer rose sharply compared to the previous high base.
Nevertheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily basket in the hypermarkets surveyed exceeded by 91 forints, at a minimum, the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints.
And the highest value of the basket was at 10 573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6 800 forints.)
Unicum and live fish prices remained almost at the level of last year, however prices for the turkey net, nuts and poppy rose sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, at Auchan, bread of one kilo a 139 forints were found only.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-liter bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it cost only 257 forints the bottle recorded included.
He only prevents this year, in terms of daily basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of her Daily Shopping Cart by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year's most expensive basket and this year's cheapest basket, we see a 12 percent difference while the difference between the cheapest of last year and this year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1 480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1 206 forints, while knowing that the impact of the VAT rate increase was already noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process perplexed trade, hypermarkets could not visibly determine which margin to apply to products as they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Because of the change in the VAT rate, the increase in daily shopping cart prices has evolved in such an excessive way that the most expensive basket was 1 720 forints higher than the value of 2006 while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was greater than 1 630 forints than last year and the prices of the cheapest increased by 1 284 forints as well.
As we moved closer to the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic price increase, in less than 20 months the prices of daily consumer items rose by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm KSH data: for some basic necessities, the statistics institute has seen a price increase of more than 30 percent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the daily basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by barely more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers occupy a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to get the sudden increase in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
According to our experiences, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long shelf food in pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important queues formed at the crates of the three hypermarkets because the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, turnover is less important in the provinces, many multinationals complain to polling companies not to even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for sustainable consumer items.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been recorded in hospitals.
Hospital hygienic conditions, insufficient number of beds, overwork of medical staff do not help block infections, says the chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also making the economy on disinfectants
Not long ago, an MRSA infection was diagnosed in the trauma department of János Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacteria was detected on a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The injured woman of a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but shortly after he had to return because of an MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to do a significant operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multidrug-resistant pathogen have been reported to the National System of Hospital Surveillance, said Karolina Böröcz, chief medical officer of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Namely that it is the number of infections caused by a multidrug-resistant pathogen that has actually been recorded in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
About two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
One-third of people carry the bacteria of Staphylococcus aureus (SA) in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by SA (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) respond well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacteria, which responds well to antibiotics, will develop a well-antibiotic-resistant bacteria that will quickly proliferate in poor hospital conditions.
In the event of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as a traumatic infection or sepsis, on elderly patients, small weights or with a weakened organism.
According to the director of the János Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily life of hospitals.
We must not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find an MRSA only the or we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the nursing staff is putting on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are carriers of MRSA, however the infection cannot always be avoided.
Sample sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but the current conditions and circumstances are not favourable in Hungarian hospitals to prevent the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
As this infection occurs mainly in hospitals and seniors' residences, hospitals should control hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological collection is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not finance these examinations.
Most cases are only born if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief physician of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has rigorous recommendations on the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, i.e. microbiological examinations should be carried out in order to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
The realization of microbiological harvesting is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that the proliferent MRSAs of one patient has another most often through medical staff.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks. However, significant deficiencies are also identified in hospitals in this area.
MRSA proliferent by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to the conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemics, the patients should be away from each other by at least 1.5 meters.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, save on disinfectants, they lack nurses, the patients are numerous, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals or preventive measures are respected, the number of infections is lower in a demonstrable manner or the proliferation of the pathogen may be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection represents exorbitant expenses for social security funds, which is why this infection is being tackled everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) raises among its priorities the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSAs) and the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens.
The commissioner, who had a fatal accident, was not drunk
