An additional 400 million euros for infrastructure
János Veres, Hungarian Minister of Finance, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed three agreements worth a total of 400 million euros on a credit line on Friday to support education, transport and environment infrastructure and energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of 300 million euro for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environment projects from the Cohesion Fund, a credit agreement worth 100 million euro of which has already been signed by the parties. This time, the signed contract concerns the use of the remaining 200 million euros.
The agreement on the appropriation of 150 million euro also concerns the budgetary financing of projects related to education.
The EIB has approved a total of 300 million euros for Hungary, the remaining 150 million euros will be able to be used later, following the extension of the credit agreement.
The parties have signed a contract of 50 million euros for innovation, the state budget will use this envelope in the first place as part of the research and development project to be carried out at the University of Debrecen.
During the negotiations, the draft of metro line 4 was also discussed.
The parties agreed that they would re-discuss the possible amendment of the initial contract once Hungary has finalised the details of the metro funding with the EU.
According to János Veres, this could be done in the first quarter of 2008.
Since 1990, the EIB has granted a total of 8.4 billion euro for the financing of 113 projects in Hungary.
The EIB grants its appropriations according to the interest rate related to EURIBOR, with a grace period of 8 years and without a commitment fee.
