The feat is not marked in red everywhere
In Hungary, the law defines exactly the days of the feast and, around the festies, it has become common to reorganize the working days whose number will decrease next year.
The parties are not uniform in the EU and the US either.
Hungarian legislation distinguishes between national and state days and days of rest.
Rest days are often related to religious parties or to important historical events.
In Hungary, we celebrate the New Year, the last day of the year that ends and the first day of the New Year are also days of rest, the latter all the more so that the electivators can rest quietly.
Moreover, in a year, we have in total eleven feeds marked in red.
March 15 is a national feat, in commemoration of the revolution of 1848, as is October 23, also the commemorative day of the 1956 revolution.
On August 20, we celebrate the constitution of our state, May 1 is the feast of work and on November 1 and 2, we remember our family members and deceased friends.
Also, we have two days at Easter, at Pentecost and at Christmas.
On the days of our state, national or religious feasts rarely falling on a weekend, depending on the calendar, it has become common to reorganize the working days in cases where there is only one working day left before or after the fete marked in red.
It is true that we pay the price of extended weekends by working or going to school the Saturday before the extended weekend.
For many years, the Minister of Labour has ruled in a particular regulation on the replacement days of the days preceding or following the feasts.
The law extends to all employers and employees, to civil servants and to persons working in the public service.
It does not, however, apply to service societies, institutions that turn uninterrupted and in service, because of their vocation, and also for days of rest.
This year, working days will be changed only around the end of the year’s feeds: from December 24, life stops almost all over the country because according to the experiences the majority of people do extra hours or takes a vacation that they have saved for these purposes to be able to spend the days between Christmas and New Year’s Day at home.
Next year a lot of feats fall in the middle or at the end of the week, therefore there will be fewer changes in workdays compared to this year.
The calendar will be reorganized the first time around the work floor to allow employees to stay at home four days in a row.
Saturday, April 25 will be a working day to have a day of rest on Friday, May 2.
Another change is planned for October 23: Saturday, October 18 will be a work day replacing Friday 24.
On the other hand, next year, the end of the year is announced under the sign of the fetes because from December 24, everyone will take a non-stop break even if the New Year's Day falls on a Wednesday.
