In the time of the Spanish, Cuba had been the bastion of their invasion of America.
Christopher Columbus called it the most beautiful place the human eye has ever seen.
Havana became the depot and place of transhipment of the treasures that the Spanish had stolen and that they were transporting to Europe.
Then came the American era.
The Hotel Nacional was erected in the very early 20's.
It was Lucky Luciano, one of the leaders of the American mafia, who had him built, since everything that was a crime in the United States (especially under prohibition) was admitted and supported in Cuba: drugs, gambling, prostitution.
Among his clients were, among others,
Winston Churchill, Ava Gardner, Frank Sinatra.
In Havana, high-rise buildings grew and cars, belonging to the cult symbols of the 50's of the last century, were circulating on the wide boulevards.
Ernest Hemingway bought a property in San Francisco de Paula, near Havana, and in Cojímar he had his yacht.
The stars of showbusiness and politicians from all over America left their signatures on the walls of the Bodeguita del Medio.
