Spectacular repair on the space station
It took more than seven hours of space work for astronaut Scott Parazynski and his crewmates at the International Space Station (ISS) to perform the spectacular repair of a torn solar panel, which is essential to the continuation of the station's scientific activities.
A risky exit that has accumulated records because of its duration, its distance from the habitable modules, the speed with which it was imagined, the tools "tinkered" by the astronauts to carry out the repair.
The problem arose Tuesday as the astronauts unloaded the Harmony module from the Discovery shuttle, a large cylindrical part tasked with hosting the European and Japanese scientific laboratories (see box).
This module is a kind of drawing dock for laboratory modules.
But we need to be able to supply them with electricity.
The second task of the crew was therefore to move a solar panel electricity production module weighing 17.5 tonnes, already present on the ISS, in order to set it up to its final position.
After moving it, the crew began the redeployment of the solar panels of the module which have a wingspan of 76 meters.
And that's where one of the panels, unfolding like accordions, was damaged on nearly a meter by a cable that got stuck.
The deployment was stopped so as not to further damage the panel.
The astronauts, who were originally scheduled to perform a control exit of the Discovery shuttle, and then go and repair another solar panel whose rotational system was defective, were forced to devote themselves to the damaged panel.
And it was Scott Parazynski who was chosen to go caracolel at the end of the 30 meters length of the remote-controlled arm of the shuttle added to that of the station to carry out the repair.
It is one of NASA's best spacewalker.
Large, resistant, very clever, it has a very developed torso and long arms.
At the age of 46, this doctor by training was therefore in charge of "operating" the "injured" solar panel.
After precisely inspecting the damage, he severed the attack cable and installed kinds of "splints" on the damaged area.
He was helped by a second spacewalker left near the airlock and, from the inside, by other astronauts including Peggy Whitson, the commander of the crew.
The tool he used, a hockey mini-channel wrapped in insulation to avoid electrocution on the solar panels producing several hundred volts, was designed and "tinkered" by the astronauts on board the station.
Once the operation was complete, Scott Parazynski waited until the panel was fully deployed before taking inventory of his tools and returning to the interior of the station.
Yesterday afternoon, the astronauts enjoyed a half-day of relaxation before today, seven astronauts return to the shuttle Discovery for a return to Earth scheduled for Wednesday.
