The new gas case between Russia and Ukraine is sounding the alarm.
A dispute over the price of gas ferments between Ukraine and Russia, thus increasing the risk of repercussions on fuel exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are transported by pipelines, and each pipe is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia increases the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two, had caused a decrease in supplies to the EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia’s property monopoly company supplying the gas, tried in vain to reach an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would rise as expected, its prices to Ukraine as it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from the neighbor Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would include for Ukraine, a 40 percent increase in import costs from Gazprom.
“It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the conversations, recalling that we are a country through which most of the gas transits,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters news agency.
“Fluctuations in gas costs would probably be linked to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine”
The last major altercation between Moscow and Kiev caused the interruption of Gazprom supplies to Ukraine in January 2006.
This has led to the fall in exports to Western Europe, thereby increasing prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supplies.
Russia has the largest stockpiles of gas, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom complements its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
