The Scottish Ministry of Health must improve the checks to be carried out on its extra-community employees to verify whether they have previous criminals, the control committee said.
The warning from the Auditor General, Robert Black, came after a foreign doctor working in Scotland was involved in the attack at Glasgow Airport in June.
M. Black further expressed concern that the Scottish Ministry of Health has no specific data on the number of people overseas it employs.
His report nevertheless highlighted other decisive checks, properly carried out on a sample of employees of five health authorities.
The Auditor General carried out checks on extra-Community staff following the Glasgow airport attack.
Bilal Addullah, 28, a doctor of Iraqi origin at the Royal Alexandra Hospital in Paisley, was arrested at the airport after rushing with his jeep to the doors of the main terminal.
He was one of the three doctors who were filmed at the Old Bailey in October, as he was suspected of being involved in various attempts to explode cars in the UK.
The Ministry of Health will have to carry out pre-employment checks on overseas staff, to be sure of the validity of their qualifications, experiences, and work permit for the United Kingdom.
Although the Scottish Ministry of Health uses the Scottish Disclosure to carry out checks on previous criminals, the agency has no right to obtain such information outside of Britain.
Among the many warnings, the Auditor General's report now states that committees are required to confront the Office of Supervisory Office of previous criminal acts, thus allowing employers to undertake controls over various countries.
"While we have discovered that some information about staff has been verified, it is not done every time," the report said.
M. Black said that the Scottish Department of Health carries out most of the pre-employment checks it would do itself, but it also added: “Our report highlights aspects where the system can be improved to ensure that adequate information on some overseas staff is available for health services.
M. Peter Terry, president of BMA Scotland, said it is "extremely unlikely" that pre-employment controls could identify employees who could commit future terrorist acts.
He said "the report suggests that the current pre-employment checks, are working well in the Scottish health system and that it is not certain that these warnings can bring any added value."
Scottish health authorities have reported employing 1161 people overseas, mostly made up of doctors and nurses.
But the general reviser stressed that these figures must certainly be revised upwards, in part because of the problems related to the identification of staff members with open-ended contracts, who may or may not choose to remain in our country.
The investigation has shown that the health authorities' current control procedures in Ayrshire and Arran, Grampian, Greater Glasgow and Clyde, Lanarkshire, and Lothian, are quite adequate.
These checks are carried out on passport, work permit and qualifications.
The Scottish Government is currently revising its policy and pre-employment control system for staff members overseas in the health service.
Health Secretary Nicola Sturgeon said: “I was excited to do this work in the wake of the terrorist attack at Glasgow airport. »
It added that the Scottish Government allied to the health committees would carefully consider the warnings set out in the report to be published next month, and would undertake to ensure a better execution of recently updated pre-employment checks, and valid for all employees, including persons overseas.
