Venus is the infernal twin of the Earth.
Despite its atmosphere hostile to life, Venus is more like Earth than previously believed: the European space probe "Venus Express" has discovered lightning in the atmosphere and wind whirlwinds at the poles, similar to those that appear in winter on Earth.
For almost three decades, scientists have assumed that there are lightning on Venus.
The European probe "Venus Express" has now provided evidence - it has detected electromagnetic waves at the edge of the atmosphere: the lightning on Venus bursts at a height of about 56 kilometers of cloud cloud, reports Christopher Russel of the University of California, Los Angeles in the scientific magazine "Nature".
According to the famous theory of cyprine, the lightning would have made life appear on Earth: the storm would have stimulated reactions in the oceans that led to the formation of amino acids, the cornerstone of life.
That’s not the case on Venus: “If there was a lifetime, it must have been on a very old date in history,” Sean Solomon of the Carnegie Institution told Washington.
There should be little living things today on the surface of Venus: the atmosphere is about a hundred times denser than on Earth, there are sometimes temperatures of 500 degrees.
"Venus may be the infernal twin of the Earth, but she remains a twin," Russell said.
Why Venus, which resembles Earth so much in mass and dimensions, has been struck by such a different evolution, is the fundamental question of the ASE mission.
The departure of "Venus Express" in November 2005 was an important step in Venusian research, since no probes were on their way to explore this planet since the 1990s.
In the opinion of the researchers, the most recent research findings that have now been presented in several articles of "Nature" do not only highlight the singularity of Venus within the solar system.
They also show that the commonalities with the Earth of our neighboring planet are more numerous than assumed at first glance.
Thus the researchers found, in addition to the already known wind vortices at the north pole, a whirlwind of clouds at the south pole, which spins much faster.
The phenomenon recalls the drafts in the terrestrial hemispheres in winter, writes a team of researchers around Giuseppe Piccioni of the Istituto di Astrofisica Spaziale e Fisica Cosmica Italian.
The second planet of the solar system has almost the same mass as the Earth and is, with a diameter of 12,100 kilometers, almost as large.
The planet qualified as an evening or morning star revolves around the sun in just 225 days.
However, it rotates much more slowly on itself: one Venusian day lasts for 243 Earth days.
Although Venus, with surface temperatures of 460 degrees Celsius and a pressure of 92 bar, hardly recalls the Earth, scientists assume that the two planets have formed under similar conditions.
On both, the water accumulated and remained on Earth in the form of oceans, but was lost in space on Venus.
And while carbon dioxide has attached itself to Earth as carbonate, it is the majority of the atmosphere on Venus.
