These are not the crates of Warhols.
The one that connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or if?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on the list of Warhol’s works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the 1968 Brillo-Boxes of the year by Andy Warhol, the internal research of the Moderna Museet in Stockholm today leads to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", whose former director of the museum Pontus Hulten made a gift in 1995 to the Moderna Museet, are copies - as well as a large number of theArt.
Ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatoric productions.
In 1964, Warhol created his first "Brillo-Boxes" in New York, painted wooden crates, which are based on the red-blue-white design of "Brillo" powdered soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet presented in 1968 - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: These did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been directly delivered from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce a few wooden boxes Brillo in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as original Brillo-Boxes of Andy Wahrol authorized, with the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them have reached more than 100 000 dollars in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum wrongly claimed, later, that about one hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, that Warhol would then have ceded to him.
In truth, the 105 crates of Hultén were produced in Malmö in 1990 only, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three others of Swedish private collections, among which two were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminated panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
The texture of the copies that date from the year 1990 reveals on the contrary that the paint was directly applied without a layer of background on the laminated panels, using a roll of paint - in addition it is not an oil painting, but an acrylic.
"These boxes have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," says the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York does not come another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection as copies.
Already in July the Authentication Board has of course announced, that it will investigate the "heavy accusations" that will be raised in the case of cases of soap powder.
But since then we have been surrounded there by an inexorable silence.
Manila rebel soldiers abandon
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers are abandoning, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who blamed the President for corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters in the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The soldiers loyal to the government had shortly before stormed the hotel with the help of tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been entrenched for hours in the building.
About half of them were standing in court on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 – among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly slip away with about 30 supporters.
The military police, who normally had to watch them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
The loyal troops in power closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The President convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' action.
“People have had enough,” said Trillanes.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who commanded before the elite unit of the Scouts Rangers, said that other units of the army soon wanted to join the march.
Critics of the regime called for a large demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by corruption blames.
The financial district of Manila was already since 2003 the scene of the mutiny attempt of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo.
The insurrection broke nearly 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have already been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
